ty high up on my list, <br />actually. The reason it didn't make it into 2.0 was that I considered it <br />less important than read caching (in general I tend to think read <br />performance is about ten times as important as write performance), and <br />because it has some very nasty issues that I didn't feel comfortable <br />about fixing in the late 1.3.x series.<br /><br />My _personal_ plans for 2.1 will be the i386 kernel mapping change (kernel<br />mapped at high virtual addresses, no separate user segment) and right after<br />that (it should be a few days of coding once I get started on the 2.1 tree)<br />I'll start on the NFS and networking stuff. <br /><br />(In fact I hope that Olaf may beat me to it when it comes to NFS - he <br />knows NFS much better than I do anyway).<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
